@page "/board"

<h1>Message Board</h1>
<p>
    This is a static preview. The real board needs a backend — see the note below for the plan.
</p>

<div class="crt-frame">
    @foreach (var t in _threads)
    {
        <div class="board-row">
            <span>@t.Title <span class="tag">@t.Machine</span></span>
            <span class="meta">@t.Replies replies · last @t.LastActive</span>
        </div>
    }
</div>

<section style="margin-top:1.5rem;">
    <h2>Build note</h2>
    <p>
        A real board needs persistence, auth, and moderation — not something to fake in the front end.
        Options, roughly in order of effort:
    </p>
    <ol>
        <li><strong>Comments-only first:</strong> attach Giscus (GitHub Discussions) per Dev Diary post — ships this week.</li>
        <li><strong>Own API:</strong> a small ASP.NET Core Web API + SQL Server for threads/replies, called from this
            page via <code>HttpClient</code>. Straightforward given the day-job stack, but is real ongoing maintenance.</li>
        <li><strong>Embed existing:</strong> Flarum or Discourse on a subdomain, skinned to match — fastest path to a
            "real" forum, least control over the look.</li>
    </ol>
</section>

@code {
    private record Thread(string Title, string Machine, int Replies, string LastActive);

    private readonly List<Thread> _threads = new()
    {
        new("Anyone still got a working 1541 disk drive?", "C64", 4, "2h ago"),
        new("CPC vs Spectrum: the loading screech debate, again", "Spectrum", 11, "1d ago"),
        new("Best modern USB joystick for CPC games?", "Amstrad", 2, "3d ago"),
    };
}
